06513nam a22009135i 9780231545846DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018052747  a97802315458467 a10.7312/hanu185102doi  a(DE-B1597)526854  a(OCoLC)1079411426  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPG3245b.N49 2019 7aDRA0160002bisacsh00aNew Russian Drama :bAn Anthology /ced. by Maksim Hanukai, Susanna Weygandt. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Library00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD. What Thomas Hobbes Knows About Today’s Russia -- tINTRODUCTION. Drama Against “Theater” and Theater After Drama -- tA CHRONOLOGY OF NEW RUSSIAN DRAMA -- tPLASTICINE -- tPLAYING THE VICTIM -- tSEPTEMBER.DOC -- tTHE BROTHERS CH. -- tTHE BLUE MACHINIST -- tTHE LOCKED DOOR -- tTHE SOLDIER -- tSUMMER WASPS STING IN NOVEMBER, TOO -- tSOMNAMBULISM -- tPROJECT “SWAN” -- tNOTES -- tABOUT THE AUTHORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew Russian Drama took shape at the turn of the new millennium—a time of turbulent social change in Russia and the former Soviet republics. Emerging from small playwriting festivals, provincial theaters, and converted basements, it evolved into a major artistic movement that startled audiences with hypernaturalistic portrayals of sex and violence, daring use of non-normative language, and thrilling experiments with genre and form. The movement’s commitment to investigating contemporary reality helped revitalize Russian theater. It also provoked confrontations with traditionalists in society and places of power, making theater once again Russia’s most politicized art form.This anthology offers an introduction to New Russian Drama through plays that illustrate the versatility and global relevance of this exciting movement. Many of them address pressing social issues, such as ethnic tensions and political disillusionment; others engage with Russia’s rich cultural legacy by reimagining traditional genres and canons. Among them are a family drama about Anton Chekhov, a modern production play in which factory workers compose haiku, and a satirical verse play about the treatment of migrant workers, as well a documentary play about a terrorist school siege and a postdramatic “text” that is only two sentences long. Both politically and aesthetically uncompromising, they chart new paths for performance in the twenty-first century. Acquainting English-language readers with these vital works, New Russian Drama challenges us to reflect on the status and mission of the theater.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aRussian dramay20th centuryvTranslations into English. 7aDRAMA / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBrothers, Presnyakov, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurnenkov, Mikhail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGremina, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanukai, Maksim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanukai, Maksim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPryazhko, Pavel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPulinovich, Yaroslava, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodionov, Andrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchechner, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchechner, Richard.1 aSigarev, Vassily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTroepolskaya, Ekaterina, 